        <h2 id="examples">Real nano-influencer campaign examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Local bakery drives weekend traffic</h3>
        <p>A local bakery sent free pastry boxes to 15 local food creators with 2,000-8,000 followers each. Combined reach: approximately 45,000 local people. Product cost: $150. Result: busiest weekend in three months. Eight customers that weekend mentioned Instagram when asked how they found the bakery — direct, attributable impact from a $150 investment.</p>

        <h3>2. D2C supplement brand 12x ROI</h3>
        <p>A D2C supplement brand recruited 100 nano-influencers from their customer base. Each received a product bundle and a unique 10%-off discount code. One post per influencer. The campaign generated $30,000 in tracked sales (through discount code attribution) from $2,500 in product investment — a 12x return on product cost.</p>

        <h3>3. B2B SaaS LinkedIn nano-influence</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company identified 20 power users with LinkedIn followings of 2,000-8,000 and offered them early access to a new feature in exchange for an honest review post. The resulting posts generated 340 leads over 6 weeks — cheaper per lead than the company's existing paid LinkedIn campaigns.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Nano-influencer vs micro-influencer — which to choose</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Choose nano when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Budget is limited — $50-$250 per creator</li>
              <li>You need hyper-local or hyper-niche reach</li>
              <li>Authentic UGC for reuse across channels</li>
              <li>You want to activate many creators simultaneously</li>
              <li>Product acceptance is the key metric (new brand awareness)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Choose micro when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need broader reach per creator (10k-100k)</li>
              <li>Category credibility matters (established niche voice)</li>
              <li>Platform algorithmic amplification is a goal</li>
              <li>Higher production quality content is required</li>
              <li>$500-$5,000 per creator budget is available</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for nano-influencer programmes</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with your own customers.</strong> The easiest nano-influencers to activate are people who already love your product. A message to your top social followers or review contributors costs nothing and converts at higher rates than outbound prospecting.</li>
          <li><strong>Give clear briefs, not scripts.</strong> Nano-influencers are valuable precisely because their content sounds genuine. Provide key talking points and disclosure requirements (FTC / ASA), but let them write in their own voice. Over-scripted content loses the authenticity advantage.</li>
          <li><strong>Use unique discount codes for tracking.</strong> Without tracking, you cannot measure ROI. A unique code per creator lets you attribute sales, calculate cost per acquisition, and identify which creators drive actual conversions vs just engagement.</li>
          <li><strong>Build long-term relationships.</strong> A creator who posts about your brand three times over six months is worth more than three different creators who post once. Repeat exposure from the same trusted source compounds credibility in their audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose nano-influencer content across channels.</strong> Authentic UGC performs well in paid social boosting. A nano-influencer's video about your product can become a paid ad that outperforms your studio-produced creative because it reads as genuine peer recommendation.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common nano-influencer mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Activating only one or two</strong> — the model requires volume. A nano-influencer programme with 5 creators won't produce measurable results. You need 20+ to see statistical patterns.</li>
          <li><strong>Choosing by follower count alone</strong> — two accounts with 5,000 followers can have wildly different engagement rates. Filter for 3%+ engagement rate at minimum; 5%+ is good; 7%+ is excellent.</li>
          <li><strong>No FTC/ASA disclosure requirement</strong> — all paid and gifted posts must be disclosed. Failure to disclose is a legal risk for the brand, not just the creator.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-scripting content</strong> — forced or corporate-sounding posts lose the authenticity that makes nano-influencers worth the effort. Brief, don't script.</li>
          <li><strong>No system for managing 50+ relationships</strong> — spreadsheets work to start; influencer management platforms (Grin, Aspire, Upfluence) become necessary at scale. Without a system, outreach, follow-up, and payment tracking become unsustainable.</li>
        </ul>

